[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The demo is intentionally a sketch. Here is the distance between this code and something you would deploy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real model libraries, not demo helpers.** The `PoissonVolumeModel` in this file is a stratified-mean baseline with linear corrections. Production replaces it with statsmodels' [GLM](https://www.statsmodels.org/stable/glm.html) using the Poisson or NegativeBinomial family for proper count regression with calibrated standard errors, with [Prophet](https://facebook.github.io/prophet/) using a Poisson likelihood and external regressors when seasonality is the dominant signal, or with the SageMaker [DeepAR built-in algorithm](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sagemaker/latest/dg/deepar.html) for multi-ED neural forecasting that shares strength across many EDs. Production replaces the `AcuityMixModel` with scikit-learn's `LogisticRegression(multi_class='multinomial')` plus calibrated probabilities (via `CalibratedClassifierCV`), with a gradient-boosted multinomial classifier (LightGBM, XGBoost) for higher accuracy on noisy real-world data, or with a small neural network for very-high-volume EDs. The demo's models are good enough to demonstrate the volume + acuity composition, the held-out evaluation, and the prediction-interval math; they are not good enough to drive ED staffing decisions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real Kinesis ingest, not synthetic stream.** The `MockStream` in this file iterates a list. Production reads HL7 v2 ADT-A04 messages (or FHIR R4 Encounter resources) from a Kinesis Data Stream or Amazon HealthLake. The aggregation Lambda parses the message structure, extracts the arrival timestamp, the ED identifier, the ESI level, and any chief complaint, redacts patient identifiers immediately, and writes the cleaned record into the hourly-arrivals S3 prefix. Late records (ADT messages that landed in the stream after the hour they describe has closed) need an explicit watermark and reconciliation pass; the demo ignores ordering entirely, but a real ED will see 5-15% of records arrive late on a normal day and 30%+ during EHR slowdowns.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real Glue Streaming ETL, not in-process aggregation.** The `aggregate_arrivals_to_hourly` function loops over Python dicts. Production runs an AWS Glue Streaming job (or EMR Serverless with Spark Structured Streaming) that consumes the Kinesis stream, applies a watermarked aggregation (typically a 30-minute slack so late records can land), writes the hourly counts to the hourly-arrivals S3 prefix partitioned by `(ed_id, date)`, and emits a `LatestHourAggregated` event to EventBridge that triggers the inference state machine. The Glue job uses the Glue service role with scoped Kinesis, S3, and KMS permissions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real SageMaker training, not pure-Python fits.** The `train_volume_and_acuity_models` function fits everything in-process. Production uses SageMaker training jobs running in parallel via the Step Functions Map state. Each training job pulls the modeling-ready dataset from S3, fits its model, captures error metrics on a held-out 90-day window, and writes a versioned model artifact to the model-artifact S3 prefix. The training image is a custom container built on the SageMaker scikit-learn base image with statsmodels, scikit-learn, and (optionally) Prophet installed. For multi-ED rollouts, the DeepAR built-in algorithm replaces per-ED training with a single multi-series model.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real SageMaker inference endpoint.** The forecast generation in this file calls model objects directly. Production calls a real SageMaker inference endpoint via `sagemaker_runtime.invoke_endpoint` with a JSON payload containing the future feature rows, parses the response, and composes the forecast records. The endpoint hosts both the volume model and the acuity model behind a single multi-model container, or as separate endpoints if their resource requirements differ significantly. Endpoint capacity is set to handle the hourly inference burst plus a safety margin; auto-scaling is rarely worth the complexity for an hourly cadence.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real DynamoDB, not MockTable.** Replace `MockTable` with `boto3.resource('dynamodb').Table(ED_FORECASTS_TABLE)`. The table needs a partition key (`ed_id`, type S), a sort key (`forecast_sort_key`, type S, formatted as `forecast_for_hour#generated_at` or `CURRENT#forecast_for_hour`), encryption-at-rest with a customer-managed KMS key, point-in-time recovery enabled, on-demand billing for unpredictable load (or provisioned with auto-scaling for predictable load), a global secondary index on `(ed_id, forecast_horizon_h)` if dashboards filter by horizon, and an item-level TTL on the historical (non-CURRENT) records so the table does not grow unbounded. Also handle the `BatchWriteItem` `UnprocessedItems` response with exponential backoff; `MockTable` ignores this case but DynamoDB returns unprocessed items under throttling.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real Step Functions orchestration.** The pipeline-orchestration logic (latest-hour aggregation -> feature refresh -> volume + acuity inference -> forecast composition -> DynamoDB load) runs as an AWS Step Functions state machine in production. Each step is a Lambda or a SageMaker invocation, with `Retry` and `Catch` blocks for transient failures, and an `EventBridge` rule that fires on the top of every hour to start the state machine. A separate state machine handles the weekly retraining cycle. Each state machine emits `ExecutionFailed` events to a CloudWatch alarm so on-call gets paged when a run fails.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Real EventBridge bus and CloudWatch alarms.** The `MockEventBus` and `MockCloudWatch` accumulate events and metrics. Production uses real `boto3.client('events').put_events(...)` and `boto3.client('cloudwatch').put_metric_data(...)`, plus CloudWatch alarms on per-horizon forecast error (alarm if MAPE exceeds tolerance for two consecutive cycles), per-horizon prediction-interval coverage (alarm if the actual fall-rate inside the 80% interval drops below 70% for a sustained window), pipeline-execution latency, DynamoDB write throttling, and SageMaker endpoint failures. The alarms feed an SNS topic that pages the on-call ML engineer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Late-record reconciliation.** ADT messages do not always arrive in order. The aggregation pipeline needs an explicit watermark (typically a 30-minute slack window after the hour closes) and a reconciliation pass that updates the hourly counts when late records land. Without this, the most recent hour's count is always wrong, and the model sees biased recent history. The demo aggregates the entire stream in one pass, which papers over the issue but does not solve it for real-time inference.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Diversion-window handling.** When the ED goes on diversion (ambulances are routed elsewhere), arrivals drop artificially. The pipeline needs a maintained diversion log (often manually entered, sometimes inferred from EMS data) and the training pipeline must either exclude diversion windows or model them with an explicit indicator. Without this, the model trains against a biased history and under-predicts true demand. The demo has no concept of diversion windows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Acuity-level reconciliation.** ESI assignment happens at triage, which can be minutes to hours after arrival. The demo's stream includes a 4% rate of ESI-unknown records but never reconciles them. Production runs a second-pass reconciliation that updates the hourly counts as triage data arrives, keeping the historical record clean for retraining. Without it, the acuity classifier learns a slightly distorted mapping.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-horizon forecast monitoring and drift detection.** The pipeline writes the forecast records but does not compare last hour's forecast against the actual count for that hour to detect drift. Production maintains a separate monitoring job that, on each new run, joins the prior run's forecasts against newly-arrived actuals to compute realized error per horizon, alarms on sustained drift, and triggers retraining outside the normal weekly cadence. Without this monitoring, the first sign of model degradation is a clinician complaining about chronic understaffing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Surge-plan trigger logic.** Forecasts are advisory, not directive. The surge-plan trigger consumes the 95th-percentile upper bound, current census, current acuity mix, current boarder count, and current staff level to decide whether to call in additional staff. Connecting these signals to a clean trigger condition is operations engineering on top of the forecast. The demo emits the forecast record but does no trigger logic; production builds a small Lambda that subscribes to the `ForecastRunCompleted` EventBridge event, reads the current operational state from a separate Operations Data Store, and emits a `SurgeAlertSuggested` event when the trigger fires.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Inpatient-census coupling.** ED throughput depends on inpatient capacity. When the hospital cannot admit boarders, the ED fills regardless of arrival rate. A pure arrival forecast misses this. Production couples the arrival forecast with the inpatient-census forecast (Recipe 12.5) and surfaces both on the charge-nurse dashboard so the staffing decision considers both.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cold-start handling for new EDs.** The pipeline assumes each ED has 18+ months of clean ADT history. EDs that have just opened, just relocated, or undergone major operational changes have history that is no longer representative. Production options include borrowing demand patterns from a similar ED (via hierarchical pooling), forecasting with a uniform prior plus rapid retraining, or carrying a configured forecast envelope until enough history accumulates. The demo does none of these; production picks one and implements it before launch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **HIPAA controls end-to-end.** The Kinesis stream uses server-side encryption with a customer-managed KMS key; the S3 prefixes use SSE-KMS with customer-managed keys; the DynamoDB table uses encryption-at-rest with a customer-managed key; SageMaker training and inference jobs run in a VPC with VPC endpoints to S3, CloudWatch Logs, and KMS; the Glue Streaming job reads and writes only encrypted data; CloudTrail logs all Kinesis, S3, DynamoDB, Glue, and SageMaker API calls; CloudWatch log groups are KMS-encrypted; IAM roles are scoped to specific resource ARNs; an AWS BAA is in place. The demo touches none of this; production cannot ship without all of it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Idempotency and audit trail.** Each pipeline run is identified by a `run_id`, all forecast records carry that run_id and the model version, the DynamoDB writes overwrite cleanly by the `(ed_id, forecast_sort_key)` key, and the model-artifact S3 writes use deterministic prefixes so a rerun produces the same output. An immutable audit log captures which model version produced which forecast, written through Kinesis Data Firehose into an Object-Lock S3 bucket sized to the institutional retention floor (typically seven years for HIPAA workloads).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Testing.** Unit tests cover the aggregation function (out-of-order records bucket correctly, ESI-unknown records route to the right key), the feature builder (lag features resolve correctly across week boundaries), the volume model (zero-variance features yield zero coefficients, holdout MAPE is computed only on non-zero rows), the acuity model (per-stratum mix sums to 1.0, the global-mix fallback fires when a stratum is empty), the forecast composer (per-acuity counts sum to the volume point estimate within rounding), and the DynamoDB write idempotency (writing the same record twice is a no-op). Integration tests run the pipeline against a known-input synthetic dataset and assert the output forecasts against expected values. End-to-end tests stand up real Kinesis, S3, DynamoDB, and EventBridge resources in a sandbox account and run the full Step Functions state machine.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Structured logging.** Replace the demo's `print` calls with `logger.info(..., extra={...})` calls that emit JSON-formatted structured logs to CloudWatch Logs. Log structural metadata only (run_id, ed_id, hour, record_count, mean_error, runtime_ms), never raw ADT message bodies, never patient identifiers, never chief-complaint text.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The shape of the gap.** The forecasting math in this file is a sketch but it is fundamentally correct. The plumbing around it (streaming ingest, late-record reconciliation, diversion handling, surge-plan trigger logic, inpatient-census coupling, security, monitoring, integration with the charge-nurse dashboard) is what takes the bulk of the engineering work. Plan for the plumbing to be 80% of the project; the modeling itself routinely surprises teams by being the easier part.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Related Resources
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - [Recipe 12.3: ED Arrival Forecasting](chapter12.03-ed-arrival-forecasting): The main recipe with the full architectural walkthrough this Python companion implements.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - [statsmodels Documentation](https://www.statsmodels.org/stable/): Python implementation of the GLM family (Poisson, NegativeBinomial) used for the volume model in production.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - [Prophet Documentation (Meta Open Source)](https://facebook.github.io/prophet/): Reference for the Prophet forecasting library that handles multiple seasonalities and external regressors.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - [Amazon SageMaker DeepAR Forecasting Algorithm](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sagemaker/latest/dg/deepar.html): Built-in SageMaker algorithm for multi-series neural forecasting at scale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - [scikit-learn LogisticRegression Documentation](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.linear_model.LogisticRegression.html): Multinomial classifier for the acuity-mix model in production.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - [Forecasting: Principles and Practice (Hyndman & Athanasopoulos)](https://otexts.com/fpp3/): Free online textbook covering classical and modern forecasting methods including count regression and multiple seasonalities.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - [AWS Step Functions Documentation](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/step-functions/latest/dg/welcome.html): Orchestration patterns for the hourly inference and weekly retraining cycles.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - [Amazon HealthLake Documentation](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/healthlake/latest/devguide/what-is-amazon-health-lake.html): For systems ingesting full FHIR rather than raw HL7 ADT.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - [MIMIC-IV-ED on PhysioNet](https://physionet.org/content/mimic-iv-ed/): De-identified ED visit data suitable for prototyping ED forecasting models with credentialed access.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - [Emergency Severity Index (ESI) Implementation Handbook (AHRQ)](https://www.ahrq.gov/patient-safety/settings/emergency-dept/esi.html): Reference for the ESI triage scale used in the acuity mix forecast.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    1410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
